00:18:14.789 --> 00:18:15.789
love books.

00:18:15.789 --> 00:18:19.539
This is like one of my favorite kinds of settings.

00:18:19.539 --> 00:18:26.010
Well, so, the way we're gonna start this morning
off is, Dr. Hayden and I are gonna ask each

00:18:26.010 --> 00:18:28.240
other questions, mostly about books.

00:18:28.240 --> 00:18:33.539
Then towards the end, we'd like to get some
questions from you.

00:18:33.539 --> 00:18:36.840
If questions pop up in your head in the beginning,
save those questions.

00:18:36.840 --> 00:18:41.499
File them away in the back of your head, and
at the end we want to hear those questions.

00:18:41.499 --> 00:18:47.080
What I'd like to first hear about is how you
fell in love with books.

00:18:47.080 --> 00:18:56.210
CARLA: Well, I had the wonderful experience
of having people around me who loved to read

00:18:56.210 --> 00:19:00.190
and one of the first things they would do
when I would go and visit my grandparents

00:19:00.190 --> 00:19:03.389
in the summer and things, is they would read
to me.

00:19:03.389 --> 00:19:09.460
The first thing I wanted to do though, was
learn how to read my own stuff.

00:19:09.460 --> 00:19:14.899
It was nice being read to, I loved it, but
I couldn't wait to start reading myself, so

00:19:14.899 --> 00:19:18.771
I could get into it and read whatever I wanted
to.

00:19:18.771 --> 00:19:19.771
I liked crime books.

00:19:19.771 --> 00:19:22.289
GENE: You liked crime books?

00:19:22.289 --> 00:19:24.909
Like, books about people doing bad things?

00:19:24.909 --> 00:19:26.110
CARLA: Yeah.

00:19:26.110 --> 00:19:28.429
So, I found this book.

00:19:28.429 --> 00:19:34.350
My grandmother, nice little lady and everything,
but she kind of liked mysteries and things

00:19:34.350 --> 00:19:35.350
like that.

00:19:35.350 --> 00:19:39.539
So, she had this book that I knew I wasn't
supposed to look at.

00:19:39.539 --> 00:19:42.590
It was called "Hollywood Babylon."

00:19:42.590 --> 00:19:45.390
How many of you all know what Babylon is?

00:19:45.390 --> 00:19:50.770
It was a wild place back in the ancient days.

00:19:50.770 --> 00:19:53.679
And Hollywood, you know where that is.

00:19:53.679 --> 00:19:56.559
It was a true crime thing, right?

00:19:56.559 --> 00:19:59.190
With all these gruesome pictures.

00:19:59.190 --> 00:20:03.890
Fatty Arbuckle, just murders and stuff.

00:20:03.890 --> 00:20:07.940
And when I would come, you know, she'd make
sure she would put it away.

00:20:07.940 --> 00:20:12.399
And of course, I spent most of my summer finding
it.

00:20:12.399 --> 00:20:14.240
And that's how I got hooked.

00:20:14.240 --> 00:20:18.590
At first, I could just look at the pictures
that were really, really gruesome.

00:20:18.590 --> 00:20:20.799
And then I want to know what it said.

00:20:20.799 --> 00:20:22.159
GENE: That's what got you.

00:20:22.159 --> 00:20:23.159
True crime?

00:20:23.159 --> 00:20:24.159
CARLA: True crime.

00:20:24.159 --> 00:20:25.390
GENE: True crime was what got Dr. Hayden into
books.

00:20:25.390 --> 00:20:26.580
CARLA: That's what got me going.

00:20:26.580 --> 00:20:27.580
GENE: That's great.

00:20:27.580 --> 00:20:28.580
That's great.

00:20:28.580 --> 00:20:30.619
For me, I grew up in a house of stories.

00:20:30.619 --> 00:20:31.769
My parents are both immigrants.

00:20:31.769 --> 00:20:34.119
My mom was born in mainland China.

00:20:34.119 --> 00:20:35.119
My dad in Taiwan.

00:20:35.119 --> 00:20:41.350
They both came to the United States for college
and met, fell in love, got married, had me.

00:20:41.350 --> 00:20:43.480
I grew up listening to their stories.

00:20:43.480 --> 00:20:45.720
Both my mom and my dad loved to tell stories.

00:20:45.720 --> 00:20:49.549
I think this is actually true of a lot of
immigrant families.

00:20:49.549 --> 00:20:54.419
A lot of parents who are from another country,
or another culture, they'll want to tell their

00:20:54.419 --> 00:20:58.450
kids stories from that country, from that
culture, as a way of building that connection.

00:20:58.450 --> 00:21:02.190
So, I heard lots of stories from Chinese culture
when I was a kid.

00:21:02.190 --> 00:21:04.519
Reading, for me, was actually kind of hard.

00:21:04.519 --> 00:21:11.110
I remember in early elementary school, my
teachers would divide us into these two groups,

00:21:11.110 --> 00:21:12.110
right?

00:21:12.110 --> 00:21:13.610
And they would name 'em- I think they were
named after colors.

00:21:13.610 --> 00:21:17.040
I think one of 'em was a red group, and one
of 'em was a blue group, but really they were

00:21:17.040 --> 00:21:18.690
the fast and slow readers.

00:21:18.690 --> 00:21:23.710
Everybody new; the colors weren't fooling
anybody, and I was definitely always on the

00:21:23.710 --> 00:21:24.710
slow side.

00:21:24.710 --> 00:21:29.119
At the very end of every month, our teacher
would make us line up by how many pages we'd

00:21:29.119 --> 00:21:32.289
read that month and I was always either last,
or second to last.

00:21:32.289 --> 00:21:36.710
It was me and my best friend, my best friend
would trade places.

00:21:36.710 --> 00:21:44.110
Eventually, the way I kind of got through
that was my mom would sit down and read to

00:21:44.110 --> 00:21:45.110
me.

00:21:45.110 --> 00:21:46.110
She would read with me.

00:21:46.110 --> 00:21:47.110
Even now though, I'm not a fast reader.

00:21:47.110 --> 00:21:51.639
What I realized is- you don't have to read
fast in order to love books, right?

00:21:51.639 --> 00:21:52.639
CARLA: Right.

00:21:52.639 --> 00:21:53.639
GENE: You just have to read.

00:21:53.639 --> 00:21:55.179
It doesn't matter how quickly or slowly you
do it.

00:21:55.179 --> 00:21:56.640
You can still
enjoy the book.

00:21:56.640 --> 00:21:57.640
CARLA: Right.

00:21:57.640 --> 00:22:02.659
And sometimes, you want to read slow so you
can get what you want out of it, or everything

00:22:02.659 --> 00:22:03.659
like that.

00:22:03.659 --> 00:22:04.659
GENE: Yes.

00:22:04.659 --> 00:22:10.789
CARLA: It pains me sometimes to hear people
of your age group, and certainly in my age

00:22:10.789 --> 00:22:14.739
group, where it made reading not fun.

00:22:14.739 --> 00:22:15.739
GENE: Yeah.

00:22:15.739 --> 00:22:19.070
CARLA: That's what the cool thing about reading
is, it's fun.

00:22:19.070 --> 00:22:23.869
But to have to go through all that, it takes
a little bit from it.

00:22:23.869 --> 00:22:27.230
GENE: Yeah, it does.

00:22:27.230 --> 00:22:33.399
I think there are ways in which learning to
enjoy reading in the beginning can make it

00:22:33.399 --> 00:22:38.129
so that you can get through some things that
are more difficult to read later, right?

00:22:38.129 --> 00:22:41.750
You'll remember the fun, and that'll push
you through some of the harder stuff that

00:22:41.750 --> 00:22:42.820
you'll have to read as you get older.

00:22:42.820 --> 00:22:47.320
CARLA: That's why when people say, "We're
gonna read to babies and little kids and everything,"

00:22:47.320 --> 00:22:51.529
that's to get them ready 'cause they know
there's something good if you figure out what

00:22:51.529 --> 00:22:53.419
all this text is.

00:22:53.419 --> 00:22:55.929
If you figure it out, you know there's a secret
in there.

00:22:55.929 --> 00:23:00.000
There's something that's really cool in there
and it gives you that.

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:01.000
GENE: Yeah.

00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:03.080
So you loved that True Crime book as a kid.

00:23:03.080 --> 00:23:04.080
Were there any other favorites?

00:23:04.080 --> 00:23:05.080
CARLA: I still have it.

00:23:05.080 --> 00:23:06.080
I kept that.

00:23:06.080 --> 00:23:07.080
GENE: Were there any other favorites?

00:23:07.080 --> 00:23:08.480
CARLA: Oh, Little Women.

00:23:08.480 --> 00:23:09.889
I like that.

00:23:09.889 --> 00:23:15.760
Louisa May Alcott, and one that I brought
here today is my all time favorite when I

00:23:15.760 --> 00:23:18.779
was a little girl, called Bright April.

00:23:18.779 --> 00:23:23.710
It was the first book that I learned about
and you see I have my Reading Without Walls

00:23:23.710 --> 00:23:31.799
bookmark, so take that when you get- The first
one, the Walter Award too.

00:23:31.799 --> 00:23:36.649
The first book that I checked out over and
over and over, to the point that I had library

00:23:36.649 --> 00:23:42.519
fines and didn't even realize it because this
book was the first book that I saw myself

00:23:42.519 --> 00:23:43.529
in.

00:23:43.529 --> 00:23:49.720
It was a little girl who had pigtails, who
was a Brownie, and she was brown, just like

00:23:49.720 --> 00:23:50.720
me.

00:23:50.720 --> 00:23:55.320
And I'm quite a bit older than you Gene.

00:23:55.320 --> 00:24:01.499
And when I was coming up, there weren't many
books that portrayed people that looked like

00:24:01.499 --> 00:24:02.499
me.

00:24:02.499 --> 00:24:05.789
Much less talked about my history or anything
like that.

00:24:05.789 --> 00:24:12.169
I just, to this day, I just love this book
because I could see myself in something that

00:24:12.169 --> 00:24:13.629
was important, like books.

00:24:13.629 --> 00:24:18.309
If books are important, but you don't see
yourself in 'em, what does that say?

00:24:18.309 --> 00:24:19.460
GENE: Yeah, yeah.

00:24:19.460 --> 00:24:22.190
Yeah, I had a similar issue.

00:24:22.190 --> 00:24:26.980
It was very hard when I was a kid, to find
characters who looked like me in the books

00:24:26.980 --> 00:24:29.799
that I was reading and in the television shows
that I was watching.

00:24:29.799 --> 00:24:30.799
CARLA: Oh yeah.

00:24:30.799 --> 00:24:33.929
GENE: I wonder if that's why I drifted towards
superhero comics.

00:24:33.929 --> 00:24:37.389
I started reading superhero comics when I
was in 5th grade.

00:24:37.389 --> 00:24:42.320
The very first superhero comic that I bought
was an issue of Superman.

00:24:42.320 --> 00:24:43.789
It was with Superman and the Atomic Knights.

00:24:43.789 --> 00:24:45.549
Y'all know who the Atomic Knights are?

00:24:45.549 --> 00:24:47.749
They're a little bit more obscure, but they're
these dudes-

00:24:47.749 --> 00:24:50.019
CARLA: There's a older gentleman.

00:24:50.019 --> 00:24:53.360
GENE: Yes, yes.

00:24:53.360 --> 00:24:54.789
The nerds have just outed themselves.

00:24:54.789 --> 00:24:55.789
CARLA: That's right.

00:24:55.789 --> 00:24:59.080
GENE: If you know who the Atomic Knights are,
you're definitely a nerd.

00:24:59.080 --> 00:25:03.460
They're these dudes who dressed up in medieval
style armor and they ride around on these

00:25:03.460 --> 00:25:04.899
giant, mutated dogs.

00:25:04.899 --> 00:25:05.899
CARLA: Ew.

00:25:05.899 --> 00:25:06.899
GENE: Yeah.

00:25:06.899 --> 00:25:07.899
It was kind of awesome.

00:25:07.899 --> 00:25:08.899
I gotta say it was kind of awesome.

00:25:08.899 --> 00:25:09.899
CARLA: Okay.

00:25:09.899 --> 00:25:14.429
GENE: I wonder if I drifted towards superheroes
because I had a hard time finding characters

00:25:14.429 --> 00:25:16.179
who look like me.

00:25:16.179 --> 00:25:21.460
Superheroes, people don't realize this, but
almost every major superhero out there; Superman,

00:25:21.460 --> 00:25:24.529
Batman, Iron Man, the Hulk.

00:25:24.529 --> 00:25:26.299
They're all created by children of immigrants.

00:25:26.299 --> 00:25:32.149
They were all created by these sons of Jewish
immigrants from Europe.

00:25:32.149 --> 00:25:35.830
And I think that's why every superhero has
these two identities.

00:25:35.830 --> 00:25:37.299
I had two identities when I was a kid.

00:25:37.299 --> 00:25:40.720
I had one name, a Chinese name that I used
at home.

00:25:40.720 --> 00:25:42.929
I had an English name that I used at school.

00:25:42.929 --> 00:25:45.200
I spoke one language at home, another one
at school.

00:25:45.200 --> 00:25:46.210
It was almost like that.

00:25:46.210 --> 00:25:49.539
It was like how Superman is both Superman
and Clark Kent.

00:25:49.539 --> 00:25:53.350
I don't even know if I was conscious of it
as a kid, but that definitely felt really

00:25:53.350 --> 00:25:54.350
familiar to me.

00:25:54.350 --> 00:26:00.169
CARLA: That idea of two cultures and how you
speak and how you are at home, and how you

00:26:00.169 --> 00:26:04.320
are outside of the home is a common theme,
I think, with a lot of cultures.

00:26:04.320 --> 00:26:06.080
GENE: Yeah, I think that's true.

00:26:06.080 --> 00:26:12.909
I think, I actually think that's one of the
best things about being an American, is that

00:26:12.909 --> 00:26:17.389
you can be an American without giving up that
core piece of yourself, you know?

00:26:17.389 --> 00:26:23.659
Because America is a collection of diverse
communities, and that's one of our strengths.

00:26:23.659 --> 00:26:28.109
CARLA: Someone once told me when we were talking
about having and being in this country where

00:26:28.109 --> 00:26:30.890
there's so many people looking all types of
ways.

00:26:30.890 --> 00:26:38.779
Just this variety is, what if you only had
one type of ice cream flavor, and you could

00:26:38.779 --> 00:26:40.679
never have anything else?

00:26:40.679 --> 00:26:41.679
GENE: Yeah.

00:26:41.679 --> 00:26:42.720
CARLA: Think about that.

00:26:42.720 --> 00:26:43.980
GENE: It would be terrible.

00:26:43.980 --> 00:26:45.110
It would be a punishment.

00:26:45.110 --> 00:26:49.330
CARLA: You may think it's good now to just
have chocolate, but it would be a punishment

00:26:49.330 --> 00:26:53.809
and how exciting it is to take- That's how
I feel about different types of books, too.

00:26:53.809 --> 00:26:58.450
GENE: So, was it your love of books that led
to you becoming a librarian?

00:26:58.450 --> 00:26:59.759
CARLA: Sure, sure.

00:26:59.759 --> 00:27:05.809
I had musical parents and I didn't have musical
talent, so I learned early on.

00:27:05.809 --> 00:27:07.649
But I always loved to read.

00:27:07.649 --> 00:27:14.999
And when I found out that there was a profession,
something that you could do to introduce and

00:27:14.999 --> 00:27:16.799
really get the excitement- I mean, look.

00:27:16.799 --> 00:27:17.799
We're right here.

00:27:17.799 --> 00:27:23.029
We're stomping our feet, we're talking about
Superman and we're doing all this cool stuff.

00:27:23.029 --> 00:27:26.929
And so, when I found out about being a librarian,
I was hooked on that, too.

00:27:26.929 --> 00:27:30.140
GENE: Was there a moment when you knew you
were gonna be a librarian?

00:27:30.140 --> 00:27:31.140
CARLA: Yes.

00:27:31.140 --> 00:27:38.309
There was a moment when I was working in a
store front library, similar to the one when

00:27:38.309 --> 00:27:40.169
I found out about ...
GENE: Okay.

00:27:40.169 --> 00:27:44.549
CARLA: Yeah, Bright April back in New York,
in Queens.

00:27:44.549 --> 00:27:48.070
I was working with a young man named Leonard.

00:27:48.070 --> 00:27:51.649
He was 10 and he would come in every day.

00:27:51.649 --> 00:27:56.029
And I was kind of an apprentice, I wasn't
a librarian yet.

00:27:56.029 --> 00:28:01.279
I hadn't even started library school, and
he would come in every day and just sit next

00:28:01.279 --> 00:28:02.450
to me.

00:28:02.450 --> 00:28:08.769
I would give him stuff, and he would draw
because a lot of the kids made fun of him.

00:28:08.769 --> 00:28:15.100
And so, just knowing, and putting the right
book with Leonard, and getting him to draw

00:28:15.100 --> 00:28:17.820
and stuff, was when I said, "Okay.

00:28:17.820 --> 00:28:18.820
This is cool stuff."

00:28:18.820 --> 00:28:20.289
GENE: That's great.

00:28:20.289 --> 00:28:22.669
I do think that maybe that's a thing, too.

00:28:22.669 --> 00:28:28.330
Maybe kids who other kids might make fun of,
often drift towards books.

00:28:28.330 --> 00:28:29.580
I was definitely one of those kids.

00:28:29.580 --> 00:28:33.640
I was a kid where other kids would make fun
of me, but I was also a kid who would make

00:28:33.640 --> 00:28:34.640
fun of other kids.

00:28:34.640 --> 00:28:36.130
I was on both sides-
CARLA: You were both.

00:28:36.130 --> 00:28:37.130
GENE: I was a jerk.

00:28:37.130 --> 00:28:38.840
I was definitely a jerk.

00:28:38.840 --> 00:28:41.450
People were jerks to me and I was also a jerk
back.

00:28:41.450 --> 00:28:47.419
CARLA: They were jerks to me and I was one
of those kids that all the, I wasn't one of

00:28:47.419 --> 00:28:49.279
the cool ones and everything.

00:28:49.279 --> 00:28:54.460
The last day of school, I'd have to run home
because all the cool girls would say they

00:28:54.460 --> 00:28:55.979
were gonna beat me up.

00:28:55.979 --> 00:28:58.789
But I could run fast.

00:28:58.789 --> 00:29:01.179
GENE: I couldn't run fast.

00:29:01.179 --> 00:29:02.950
CARLA: See, so you had to fight back.

00:29:02.950 --> 00:29:03.950
GENE: Yeah.

00:29:03.950 --> 00:29:05.240
CARLA: You had to be a jerk, too.

00:29:05.240 --> 00:29:07.179
GENE: Yeah, I had to be a jerk, too.

00:29:07.179 --> 00:29:12.830
But, I do think working on books, writing
and drawing, is a way of working that stuff

00:29:12.830 --> 00:29:13.830
out.

00:29:13.830 --> 00:29:17.910
If you have problems in your life- I think
all of us do.

00:29:17.910 --> 00:29:20.960
Writing and drawing is a great way of just
figuring that out for yourself.

00:29:20.960 --> 00:29:25.869
I have a friend who's an art teacher, teaches
art at a high school and he says out of all

00:29:25.869 --> 00:29:32.899
of the classes that a kid takes in high school,
the art class is the only one where the subject

00:29:32.899 --> 00:29:33.899
is themselves.

00:29:33.899 --> 00:29:34.899
CARLA: Wow.

00:29:34.899 --> 00:29:35.899
GENE: They're trying to figure themselves
out by making art.

00:29:35.899 --> 00:29:40.129
I think that's true, not just of drawing,
but also of any kind of art, including writing.

00:29:40.129 --> 00:29:41.700
CARLA: What about music, too?

00:29:41.700 --> 00:29:42.820
And stuff like that.

00:29:42.820 --> 00:29:43.820
GENE: Yeah, music too.

00:29:43.820 --> 00:29:44.820
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:29:44.820 --> 00:29:48.970
I think that's why sometimes if you have things
that are painful in your life, you can find

00:29:48.970 --> 00:29:51.669
a little bit of healing by writing and by
drawing.

00:29:51.669 --> 00:29:54.529
CARLA: So, did you and I have to ask you this.

00:29:54.529 --> 00:29:58.679
In drawing superheroes and things like that,
did you get any revenge?

00:29:58.679 --> 00:30:06.929
GENE: Did I make up bad guys based on ... I
don't think I ever did it consciously 'cause

00:30:06.929 --> 00:30:11.749
I was worried about getting in trouble, but
the very first superhero comic I did was in

00:30:11.749 --> 00:30:12.749
fifth grade.

00:30:12.749 --> 00:30:16.549
I did it with my friend Jeremy Kinioshi, who
was half Jewish and half Japanese.

00:30:16.549 --> 00:30:21.390
We were both the comic book kids in our class.

00:30:21.390 --> 00:30:25.249
During lunch when our more athletic friends
were playing tetherball- Do y'all still play

00:30:25.249 --> 00:30:26.249
tetherball?

00:30:26.249 --> 00:30:27.249
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:30:27.249 --> 00:30:28.249
GENE: It's awesome, right?

00:30:28.249 --> 00:30:29.549
Except that I was terrible at it.

00:30:29.549 --> 00:30:31.570
The ball would always hit me in the head.

00:30:31.570 --> 00:30:35.519
So, instead of playing tetherball, Jeremy
and I would sit at the tables and we would

00:30:35.519 --> 00:30:36.519
draw comics together.

00:30:36.519 --> 00:30:40.919
Then we would give our originals to his mom,
who would take 'em to work with her and wait

00:30:40.919 --> 00:30:44.629
till all of her coworkers went home and sneak
photocopies for us.

00:30:44.629 --> 00:30:48.060
We would take these photocopies, we stapled
them by hand to make our own comics, and we

00:30:48.060 --> 00:30:51.509
sold our comics to our classmates for 50 cents
a piece.

00:30:51.509 --> 00:30:52.509
It was awesome.

00:30:52.509 --> 00:30:53.509
We made $8.

00:30:53.509 --> 00:30:54.509
It was the best.

00:30:54.509 --> 00:30:58.779
Nowadays, if you want to do the same thing
you cannot sell for 50 cents.

00:30:58.779 --> 00:30:59.779
Prices have gone up.

00:30:59.779 --> 00:31:03.190
You've gotta charge at least $1.50, but it
was great.

00:31:03.190 --> 00:31:04.190
It was great.

00:31:04.190 --> 00:31:08.479
I think working on that comic taught me how
to tell stories.

00:31:08.479 --> 00:31:12.629
Working on that comic gave me a way of- I
was also a pretty shy kid, too.

00:31:12.629 --> 00:31:14.120
It was weird, right?

00:31:14.120 --> 00:31:16.789
Being shy and also a jerk, but I was a pretty
shy kid.

00:31:16.789 --> 00:31:20.470
So working on that comic gave me a way of
expressing myself in ways that I couldn't

00:31:20.470 --> 00:31:22.490
by just talking.

00:31:22.490 --> 00:31:24.549
CARLA: How did the stories come to you?

00:31:24.549 --> 00:31:27.289
Did you just wake up and-
GENE: Okay.

00:31:27.289 --> 00:31:33.450
When I was in fifth grade, I thought I was
kind of like a ... I thought I was super creative

00:31:33.450 --> 00:31:34.450
and stuff.

00:31:34.450 --> 00:31:35.450
So, I thought, "Oh man.

00:31:35.450 --> 00:31:39.529
I just woke up in this character form, fully
informed in my head."

00:31:39.529 --> 00:31:43.441
But then as an adult, I look back on the character
we made up and I realize no, he was actually

00:31:43.441 --> 00:31:44.441
just a rip off.

00:31:44.441 --> 00:31:51.059
He was a rip off character of Robin Hood 'cause
he wore all green and he lived in the woods

00:31:51.059 --> 00:31:54.820
and he had a band of friends that he used
to call his "Merry Men", just like Robin Hood.

00:31:54.820 --> 00:31:56.440
CARLA: Yeah, I think that's pretty close.

00:31:56.440 --> 00:31:57.700
GENE: Yes, isn't it?

00:31:57.700 --> 00:31:58.700
It's a little close.

00:31:58.700 --> 00:31:59.700
CARLA: Yeah.

00:31:59.700 --> 00:32:00.770
GENE: But, there was one difference.

00:32:00.770 --> 00:32:04.529
The difference was, our character, instead
of fighting with a bow and arrow, he actually

00:32:04.529 --> 00:32:08.200
had a discus of death that he would throw
at people's heads.

00:32:08.200 --> 00:32:10.649
CARLA: You were kind of a True Crime fantasy
stuff.

00:32:10.649 --> 00:32:11.649
GENE: A little bit.

00:32:11.649 --> 00:32:17.139
CARLA: Yeah, that was a little bit of-
GENE: You know, I actually think now, as an

00:32:17.139 --> 00:32:21.899
adult, even though that one character was
terrible, I do think sometimes kids think

00:32:21.899 --> 00:32:26.129
creativity is just like when you make stuff
up out of nothing.

00:32:26.129 --> 00:32:27.929
But that's almost never true.

00:32:27.929 --> 00:32:30.619
You can't make stuff up out of nothing.

00:32:30.619 --> 00:32:37.590
What real creativity is, I think, is combining
things together that were never combined before.

00:32:37.590 --> 00:32:41.129
So, if you love superheroes and you take something
else that you love- I don't know.

00:32:41.129 --> 00:32:42.139
Maybe like, chocolate cake.

00:32:42.139 --> 00:32:46.679
And you figure out a way to make a superhero
based on chocolate cake, that'll be a really

00:32:46.679 --> 00:32:47.679
creative idea.

00:32:47.679 --> 00:32:48.679
CARLA: Let's work on that one.

00:32:48.679 --> 00:32:49.679
GENE: Yeah.

00:32:49.679 --> 00:32:50.679
I agree.

00:32:50.679 --> 00:32:53.679
CARLA: It's something, though, when you think
about.

00:32:53.679 --> 00:32:55.220
So, what are you working on now?

00:32:55.220 --> 00:32:57.379
What is the Reading Without Walls?

00:32:57.379 --> 00:32:59.090
GENE: Yes.

00:32:59.090 --> 00:33:01.629
CARLA: Don't forget the bookmarks and everything.

00:33:01.629 --> 00:33:02.669
GENE: That's right.

00:33:02.669 --> 00:33:09.259
Two January's ago, I was in this very room,
in January of 2016.

00:33:09.259 --> 00:33:13.759
The Library of Congress, Every Child a Reader,
and the Children's Book Council, they gave

00:33:13.759 --> 00:33:15.229
me this fancy medal.

00:33:15.229 --> 00:33:17.869
To this day, this is the fanciest thing I
own.

00:33:17.869 --> 00:33:21.320
This is as bling-bling as Gene Yang gets.

00:33:21.320 --> 00:33:23.299
If you want to touch this, come up later.

00:33:23.299 --> 00:33:24.299
I'll let you touch it.

00:33:24.299 --> 00:33:25.299
It's kind of awesome.

00:33:25.299 --> 00:33:26.299
CARLA: It's got your name engraved, too.

00:33:26.299 --> 00:33:27.299
GENE: Yeah, it's got my name on the back.

00:33:27.299 --> 00:33:28.299
CARLA: I see it.

00:33:28.299 --> 00:33:29.299
Oh, cool.

00:33:29.299 --> 00:33:30.489
GENE: Yeah, it's got my name on the back and
they named me the fifth national ambassador

00:33:30.489 --> 00:33:32.590
for young people's literature.

00:33:32.590 --> 00:33:40.110
Which just means that, for my two year term;
2016 and 2017, my job is to get both more

00:33:40.110 --> 00:33:42.289
kids reading and kids reading more.

00:33:42.289 --> 00:33:45.580
The way I'm doing that is, I've been going
around the country issuing what I call the

00:33:45.580 --> 00:33:47.629
"Reading Without Walls Challenge."

00:33:47.629 --> 00:33:52.659
You know, one of the best things about growing
up is you all get to explore the world.

00:33:52.659 --> 00:33:56.580
That's your primary job right now, is to figure
out how the world works.

00:33:56.580 --> 00:34:03.080
And books are a great way of exploring the
world, so I want us all to read books outside

00:34:03.080 --> 00:34:04.169
of our comfort zones.

00:34:04.169 --> 00:34:07.230
Read books that are actually exploring books.

00:34:07.230 --> 00:34:10.440
Books that are not the normal books that we
would read.

00:34:10.440 --> 00:34:14.270
So, the challenge works like this; you could
either do this as a community, or you can

00:34:14.270 --> 00:34:15.849
do this just as an individual reader.

00:34:15.849 --> 00:34:17.450
You set yourself a due date.

00:34:17.450 --> 00:34:20.230
By that due date, just do one of three things.

00:34:20.230 --> 00:34:24.060
Number one, you can read a book about a character
who doesn't look like you or live like you.

00:34:24.060 --> 00:34:26.040
Somebody who's very different from you.

00:34:26.040 --> 00:34:30.440
Two, you could read a book about a topic that
you might not know anything about.

00:34:30.440 --> 00:34:32.660
Something that you might even find intimidating.

00:34:32.660 --> 00:34:37.080
Or three, you can read a book in a format
that you normally wouldn't read for fun.

00:34:37.080 --> 00:34:41.510
