00:49:55.580 --> 00:50:02.490
And every day that I'm here, I put up something
cool that I've found and I've seen.

00:50:02.490 --> 00:50:09.500
Like Thomas Jefferson's handwriting in his
own hand when he was working on the Declaration

00:50:09.500 --> 00:50:10.560
of Independence.

00:50:10.560 --> 00:50:15.490
And Seeing him and what he put in, and what
he took out.

00:50:15.490 --> 00:50:20.530
I think people don't realize there are drafts
of certain things that you hear about, but

00:50:20.530 --> 00:50:24.220
they did a lot of cross outs and thought about
things.

00:50:24.220 --> 00:50:29.280
And it's really nice to see, okay, this didn't
come up just perfect.

00:50:29.280 --> 00:50:30.530
That they had to work on it.

00:50:30.530 --> 00:50:31.530
GENE: Yeah.

00:50:31.530 --> 00:50:37.230
I actually think that that was something that
I had to learn as I grew up and started making

00:50:37.230 --> 00:50:38.920
stories as an adult.

00:50:38.920 --> 00:50:43.280
When I was a kid and I read books, I always
thought, "Man, this came into that author's

00:50:43.280 --> 00:50:45.170
head perfectly formed.

00:50:45.170 --> 00:50:47.970
They just wrote it down and sent it to the
publisher.

00:50:47.970 --> 00:50:49.310
The publisher made it into a book."

00:50:49.310 --> 00:50:52.440
After I got into books, I realized that is
not the case at all.

00:50:52.440 --> 00:50:55.140
That there's so much revision that happens.

00:50:55.140 --> 00:50:58.841
There's so much stuff where you write something
down and you're not super satisfied with it.

00:50:58.841 --> 00:51:02.860
You just change it and change it, and tweak
it and tweak it until it gets to where you

00:51:02.860 --> 00:51:03.860
want it to be.

00:51:03.860 --> 00:51:07.470
I would say maybe even half of writing, half
of making stories, is that.

00:51:07.470 --> 00:51:09.332
CARLA: Is changing and making-
GENE: Yeah.

00:51:09.332 --> 00:51:13.770
CARLA: So when you see that even the Declaration
of Independence, there were cross outs and

00:51:13.770 --> 00:51:16.570
there were thoughts and there were things
like that.

00:51:16.570 --> 00:51:19.130
And Abraham Lincoln, the Gettysburg address.

00:51:19.130 --> 00:51:22.980
To see his whole handwriting and what he thought.

00:51:22.980 --> 00:51:26.943
GENE: Even somebody like Abraham Lincoln couldn't
get it right the first time, right?

00:51:26.943 --> 00:51:28.660
CARLA: Couldn't get it right the first time,
but he worked on it.

00:51:28.660 --> 00:51:29.660
GENE: Had to go back and change it.

00:51:29.660 --> 00:51:34.960
CARLA: And the thing about Abraham Lincoln,
that wonderful speech that he gave was the

00:51:34.960 --> 00:51:37.130
shortest speech that day.

00:51:37.130 --> 00:51:39.171
One guy gave a speech for three hours.

00:51:39.171 --> 00:51:42.260
Can you imagine?

00:51:42.260 --> 00:51:43.910
One speech, three hours.

00:51:43.910 --> 00:51:46.830
And Abraham Lincoln got up and it was five
minutes.

00:51:46.830 --> 00:51:51.740
They said that was the best speech of the
day because it was short and to the point.

00:51:51.740 --> 00:51:53.600
GENE: Yeah, yeah.

00:51:53.600 --> 00:51:59.130
Another thing that I had to learn as a professional
writer is that, often longer doesn't mean

00:51:59.130 --> 00:52:00.130
better.

00:52:00.130 --> 00:52:04.670
I remember when I was in high school and I
would write things for my English class, I

00:52:04.670 --> 00:52:12.060
would always try to make my sentences as long
as possible and I would put in as many big

00:52:12.060 --> 00:52:14.320
words as I could.

00:52:14.320 --> 00:52:16.330
Words where I barely even understood what
they meant.

00:52:16.330 --> 00:52:17.330
CARLA: Right.

00:52:17.330 --> 00:52:20.710
GENE: I wanted to do it because I felt like
it would make me sound smarter.

00:52:20.710 --> 00:52:26.530
But, now, as an adult, as a professional writer,
I realize what makes you sound smart is actually

00:52:26.530 --> 00:52:28.070
just being clear.

00:52:28.070 --> 00:52:33.220
If you can say something as clearly as possible,
as simply as possible, that is the best and

00:52:33.220 --> 00:52:35.440
the smartest way of saying it.

