01:06:07.270 --> 01:06:09.800
I've maybe done ... I don't know.

01:06:09.800 --> 01:06:12.040
12 books now?

01:06:12.040 --> 01:06:16.150
Then I have also worked on the Avatar Last
Air Bender comics.

01:06:16.150 --> 01:06:21.030
I did 15 volumes of that so far, so I've done
a lot.

01:06:21.030 --> 01:06:22.030
CARLA: Wow.

01:06:22.030 --> 01:06:32.820
GENE: Yes, young man in the ...
AUDIENCE: What's your favorite book?

01:06:32.820 --> 01:06:33.920
Comic book?

01:06:33.920 --> 01:06:41.850
GENE: My favorite book when I was a kid ... I'm
really sad that it's been a little bit forgotten,

01:06:41.850 --> 01:06:44.690
so I want you all to try to read this book
today.

01:06:44.690 --> 01:06:47.650
I love the Book of Three.

01:06:47.650 --> 01:06:50.310
It's a series of books by Lloyd Alexander.

01:06:50.310 --> 01:06:52.910
They were my favorite.

01:06:52.910 --> 01:06:56.620
As a librarian, you must've seen that go out
a lot, right?

01:06:56.620 --> 01:06:57.620
CARLA: Lord.

01:06:57.620 --> 01:06:59.160
GENE: My generation loved that book.

01:06:59.160 --> 01:07:01.430
It seems like-
CARLA: It's been lost-

01:07:01.430 --> 01:07:04.310
GENE: It's been a little bit lost-
CARLA: But it's really cool.

01:07:04.310 --> 01:07:06.150
GENE: I'm trying to bring it back.

01:07:06.150 --> 01:07:07.150
CARLA: Good.

01:07:07.150 --> 01:07:08.150
Lloyd Alexander, classic.

01:07:08.150 --> 01:07:09.250
GENE: Yeah, I love Lloyd Alexander.

01:07:09.250 --> 01:07:13.760
Then in terms of comic books, you know March
is a really great comic book.

01:07:13.760 --> 01:07:15.480
You all ought to read that.

01:07:15.480 --> 01:07:18.240
There's just a ton of comic books that I love.

01:07:18.240 --> 01:07:19.830
I don't know if I could pick one favorite.

01:07:19.830 --> 01:07:22.190
I really do love Mouse, though.

01:07:22.190 --> 01:07:23.950
It's a little bit older.

01:07:23.950 --> 01:07:26.110
It's a non-fiction book about the Holocaust.

01:07:26.110 --> 01:07:31.220
It's a really sad, and heart wrenching book,
but I think it's brilliantly done.

01:07:31.220 --> 01:07:35.310
CARLA: Then I have a question.

01:07:35.310 --> 01:07:36.670
Go ahead.

01:07:36.670 --> 01:07:38.030
GENE: Yes.

01:07:38.030 --> 01:07:45.119
AUDIENCE: What was the first book that the
Library of Congress had in their library?

01:07:45.119 --> 01:07:46.850
GENE: That's a great question.

01:07:46.850 --> 01:07:47.850
Wow!

01:07:47.850 --> 01:07:49.560
I want to know, too.

01:07:49.560 --> 01:07:52.310
CARLA: I don't know.

01:07:52.310 --> 01:07:53.340
The first book.

01:07:53.340 --> 01:08:00.750
There were about two or three hundred books
in 1800.

01:08:00.750 --> 01:08:04.690
The Library was actually part of the capital.

01:08:04.690 --> 01:08:09.660
They had books like the Bible and some other
books that they thought that it would be good-

01:08:09.660 --> 01:08:13.510
Dictionaries and things that they thought
it would be good for Congress.

01:08:13.510 --> 01:08:18.350
Thank you for asking that 'cause I'm gonna
find out, what was the very first book that

01:08:18.350 --> 01:08:20.180
someone purchased for the library.

01:08:20.180 --> 01:08:21.350
GENE: That's great.

01:08:21.350 --> 01:08:24.520
Can you give us some of the highlights of
the collection?

01:08:24.520 --> 01:08:26.029
CARLA: Oh my goodness.

01:08:26.029 --> 01:08:27.029
Highlights.

01:08:27.029 --> 01:08:32.259
Well, you have books that go back to the 12th
Century.

01:08:32.259 --> 01:08:39.510
You have the first Bible, right outside here,
that was ever printed with type.

01:08:39.510 --> 01:08:42.060
So the Gutenberg Bible.

01:08:42.060 --> 01:08:43.859
That was something- 1500.

01:08:43.859 --> 01:08:50.009
Then you have books that you would call them
"graphic" now.

01:08:50.009 --> 01:08:55.529
Audubon books with the beautiful birds and
all types of things.

01:08:55.529 --> 01:08:56.969
There's so many things.

01:08:56.969 --> 01:08:59.010
That's what's so wonderful about it.

01:08:59.010 --> 01:09:00.870
GENE: Yeah.

01:09:00.870 --> 01:09:01.870
It's a magical place.

01:09:01.870 --> 01:09:02.950
You all feel the magic, right?

01:09:02.950 --> 01:09:03.950
Sitting in this room?

01:09:03.950 --> 01:09:06.900
CARLA: Well, we were stomping around.

01:09:06.900 --> 01:09:10.880
GENE: Young man in the red.

01:09:10.880 --> 01:09:15.529
AUDIENCE: Earlier you were telling me and
my friends about Frog Man, so-

01:09:15.529 --> 01:09:16.529
GENE: Oh yeah.

01:09:16.529 --> 01:09:17.529
CARLA: Frog Man?

01:09:17.529 --> 01:09:21.799
GENE: Yeah, earlier we were hanging out and
they were asking me what my favorite superhero

01:09:21.799 --> 01:09:22.799
was.

01:09:22.799 --> 01:09:24.410
And Frogman is definitely one of my favorite
superheroes.

01:09:24.410 --> 01:09:28.020
He's an obscure character from the Marvel
universe.

01:09:28.020 --> 01:09:33.839
He doesn't have any super powers; he just
wears a costume that makes him look like a

01:09:33.839 --> 01:09:34.839
frog.

01:09:34.839 --> 01:09:44.250
So, his whole thing is this; he is the son
of a super villain named the "Leap Frog",

01:09:44.250 --> 01:09:47.450
who would use his frog suit to go and rob
banks.

01:09:47.450 --> 01:09:52.190
Then he finds out that his dad is this criminal
and he feels really bad about it, so he steals

01:09:52.190 --> 01:09:56.120
the suit from his dad and becomes a superhero
called "Frog Man".

01:09:56.120 --> 01:10:00.280
CARLA: And his super powers are?
GENE: His super powers, at the bottom of his

01:10:00.280 --> 01:10:03.720
suit, on each of his feet, are giant springs.

01:10:03.720 --> 01:10:07.740
He can just jump around and that's his whole
power.

01:10:07.740 --> 01:10:09.110
Yeah.

01:10:09.110 --> 01:10:12.210
CARLA: I'm learning a lot.

01:10:12.210 --> 01:10:14.330
It's good.

01:10:14.330 --> 01:10:16.450
GENE: Yep?

01:10:16.450 --> 01:10:22.082
AUDIENCE: Do you write and illustrate your
books, or does somebody else do it?

01:10:22.082 --> 01:10:23.260
GENE: Do I write and illustrate my books?

01:10:23.260 --> 01:10:24.500
It depends on the book.

01:10:24.500 --> 01:10:27.885
So, there are some books where I do both the
writing and the drawing, and there are other

01:10:27.885 --> 01:10:30.740
books where I only do the writing and somebody
else does the drawing.

01:10:30.740 --> 01:10:32.800
I work with a friend of mine who does the
drawing.

01:10:32.800 --> 01:10:34.630
So it depends on the book.

